The paper studies a class of strategic games played on undirected graphs, which suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories. However, the focus on equilibrium assignments and social welfare and diversity perspectives narrows down the possibilities. 

cs.GT (Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category, as the paper explicitly mentions studying equilibrium assignments and computational complexity. 

cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is also likely, as the games are played on graphs and the paper considers diversity perspectives. 

cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is a possibility, as the paper discusses computational complexity and algorithmic solutions. 

cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is another possibility, as the paper deals with strategic decision-making and maximizing utility. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the least likely sub-category, but still a possibility, as the paper deals with learning and optimization in games.
